  "slug": "steak-and-ale-pie",
  "title": "Steak and ale pie",
  "subtitle": "Chuck steak braised in stout, suet-pastry lid.",
  "excerpt": "Cubes of chuck steak browned hard and slow-braised in stout with onions, mushrooms, and thyme until the gravy is dark and the meat falls. Spooned into a pie dish, topped with a suet pastry lid, and baked until the crust is golden. Serves four to six.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Mrs Beeton, Book of Household Management (1861, Project Gutenberg #10136), 'Beef Steak Pie', as the suet-crust prototype. The use of stout in place of broth is a twentieth-century pub refinement; Beeton uses water and a glass of ale. USDA / NCHFP guidance on minimum braising temperatures (above 80°C for collagen breakdown).",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Cubed chuck steak browned hard, then slow-braised for two and a half hours with onions, chestnut mushrooms, thyme, bay, and a generous pour of stout. The gravy reduces to a dark glossy sauce; the meat reaches the falling-tender state where a spoon parts it. Cooled, spooned into a deep pie dish, topped with a suet-pastry lid brushed with egg, baked until the crust is gold and the gravy bubbles through the steam slits.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Chuck is the right cut: well-marbled, full of connective tissue that breaks down to gelatine over a slow braise, making the gravy thick and silky as it cools. Cheaper cuts like shin work too with another hour added. Don't use sirloin or rump; they tighten and dry over the long cook.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
