      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Brown the meat hard",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Toss {{beef-chuck}} of cubed beef with {{plain-flour}} of flour, salt, and pepper. Heat {{rapeseed-oil}} of oil in a heavy Dutch oven over a hot hob. Brown the meat in three batches; don't crowd the pan or it steams. Each batch wants two minutes a side. Lift to a plate. The dark fond left in the pan is half the flavour of the gravy.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Soften the onions and mushrooms",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Drop the heat. Cook {{onion}} of sliced onions for 10 minutes until soft and golden. Add {{mushrooms-chestnut}} of mushrooms; cook 5 minutes, stirring, until they release their water and start to brown. Stir in {{garlic}} of crushed garlic; cook one more minute.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Deglaze with stout",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Stir in {{tomato-puree}} of tomato purée. Cook for a minute. Pour in {{stout}} of stout and scrape the fond off the base with a wooden spoon. Reduce by a third over high heat, 4 minutes. Return the beef and any resting juices. Pour in {{stock-beef}} of hot stock and {{worcestershire-sauce}} of Worcestershire. Tuck in the {{thyme}} of thyme and the {{bay-leaves}} of bay.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Braise slowly",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Bring to a bare simmer. Cover and cook on the lowest hob setting for 2 hours, or in a 150°C oven for the same time. Check now and then; if the gravy needs thickening at the end, simmer uncovered for 10 minutes. The meat should yield to a spoon. Cool the filling for at least 30 minutes, pouring hot filling into a pastry-lined dish melts the suet pastry into the sauce.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Make the suet pastry",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Combine {{self-raising-flour}} of self-raising flour, {{sea-salt-fine}} of salt, and {{lard}} of shredded suet or grated cold lard in a bowl. Stir in {{water}} of cold water with a knife to a soft dough. Bring together with your hands; don't overwork. Roll out on a floured board to 1 cm thick, big enough to cover your pie dish with overhang. ",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": []
          },
          {
            "text": "Suet pastry",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termId": "cmp5nkio20000wkv40ikrkhod"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": " puffs in the oven and tears handsomely with a spoon.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Assemble and bake",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat the oven to 200°C (180°C fan). Spoon the cooled filling into a 1.5 L pie dish. Brush the rim with beaten egg. Drape the pastry over the top. Trim the overhang to a finger's width and crimp with a fork. Cut a 5 cm slit in the middle to let steam escape. Brush all over with {{eggs}} beaten egg. Bake 25 minutes until the pastry is deep gold and the filling bubbles through the slit.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Rest before serving",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Rest the pie for 15 minutes after it comes out of the oven. The filling thickens; the pastry stays crisp. Serve with mashed potato and buttered greens; the gravy is rich enough that nothing else is needed.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Troubleshooting",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "intro": null,
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Use chuck or shin. Ensure a steady simmer; chuck wants 80°C+ to break down. Add another hour if needed.",
              "cause": "Wrong cut, or simmer too gentle.",
              "symptom": "Meat chewy after 2 hours"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Reduce uncovered for 10 minutes at the end. Always add hot stock to a hot pan.",
              "cause": "Lid trapped too much steam, or stock added too cold.",
              "symptom": "Gravy thin"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Cool the filling for at least 30 minutes. Some cooks chill overnight.",
              "cause": "Hot filling under the lid.",
              "symptom": "Pastry soggy underneath"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Bring to room temperature before baking, or bake at 180°C for 35 minutes from cold.",
              "cause": "Pie too cold from the fridge when it went in.",
              "symptom": "Pastry browned, gravy not bubbling"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Reduce by a third, not half; the bitterness concentrates if you push it further.",
              "cause": "Stout reduced too hard.",
              "symptom": "Filling bitter"
            }
          ],
          "heading": "Common problems"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Steak and ale is the gastropub icon of British pie cookery. Eaten on dark Friday evenings with a pint of the same stout that went into the gravy, it speaks of slow heat and patient cooking. The Victorian household manuals called it 'beef-steak pie' and used water; the stout came later, when British brewing met British baking and the two refused to part.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
